      <li>
        <title>Course Description</title>

        <p>
          An exploration of numerical, graphical, and symbolic approaches to function concepts with emphasis
on real-world applications, modeling, and problem-solving skills. Topics include polynomial and
rational functions, equations and inequalities, systems of linear equations, and the connection
between functions and their graphs. 
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <title>Prerequisite</title>

        <p>
          Satisfactory score on the mathematics placement.  Also, our course is a prerequisite other courses, including MATH 180 Precalculus.
Some of them require you to earn at least a C in MATH 123.
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <title>Homework</title>

        <p>
          All homework will appear in <url href="https://www.myopenmath.com/">MyOpenMath</url>.
        </p>

      </li>



      <li>
        <title>Textbook</title>

        <p>
          <pubtitle>College Algebra</pubtitle>
          by OpenStax (5th edition). <url href="https://openstax.org/details/books/college-algebra-2e" visual="openstax/precalculus">Read Online</url>
        </p>

        <blockquote>
          <title>Reading Mathematics</title>
          <p>
            <q>
              Don’t just read it; fight it!
              Ask your own questions, look for your own examples, discover your own proofs.
              Is the hypothesis necessary?
              Is the converse true?
              What happens in the classical special case?
              What about the degenerate cases?
              Where does the proof use the hypothesis?
            </q>
          </p>

          <attribution><url href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Halmos" visual="wikipedia/Paul_Halmos">Paul Halmos</url></attribution>
        </blockquote>
      </li>
 
    </dl>
  </p>


</section>